    <h2 style="color: brown;">List</h2>
    <p>The HTML list tag is used to group related pieces of information.</p>
    <ol><li>Ordered List</li>
    <li>Unordered List</li>
<li>Description List</li></ol>
    <h3>Ordered List</h3>
    <ol type="a"><li>Ordered List or Numbered List (ol) In HTML, all the list items in an ordered list are marked with numbers by default instead of bullets.</li>
         <li>An ordered list can be numerical or alphabetical.</li></ol>
<h3>Unordered List</h3>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;"><li>An unordered list is used to create a list of items in no particular order i.e. the order of items is not relevant. </li>
    <li>By default, the items in this list will be marked with bullets. </li></ul>
    <h3>Description List</h3>
        <p>A description list is a list of terms, with a description of each term.</p>
    </h3>
    <h2 style="color: brown;">Attributes</h2>
    <p>Attributes provides additional information to the elements.</p>
    <dl><dt><b>src attribute</b><dt><dd>The src attribute specifies the path to the image to be disply.</dd><dt><b>href attribute</b></dt><dd>The href attribute specifies the URL of the page the link.</dd><dt><b>style attribute</b></dt><dd>The style attribute is used to add styles to an element, such as color, font, size, and more.</dd><dt><b>width and height attribute</b></dt><dd>The image tag should also contain the width and height attributes, which specify the width and height of the image (in pixels).
</dd></dl>
    <h2 style="color: brown;">Tables</h2>
    <p>HTML tables allow web developers to arrange data into rows and columns.</p>
    <table><caption><b>Student Marks</b></caption><tr><th>S.No</th>
        <th>Name</th>
        <th>Subject</th>
        <th>Marks</th></tr>
    <tr><td rowspan="4">1</td><td rowspan="4">Deepthi</td></tr>
       <tr><td>Telugu</td>
        <td>90</td></tr>
    <tr><td>English</td>
    <td>80</td></tr>
<tr><td>Social</td>
<td>70</td></tr></table>
<h2 style="color: brown;">Class</h2>
<p>The HTML <span class="attribute">class</span> attribute is used to specify a <span class="attribute">class</span> for an HTML element. We can call the <span class="attribute">class</span> with the use of ".".</p>
<h2 style="color:brown;">Id</h2>
<p>The HTML id attribute is used to specify a unique id for an HTML element. We can call the id with the use of "#".
</p>
<p id="ID">ID Attribute</p>
<h2 style="color: brown;">Forms</h2>
<p>An HTML form is used to collect user input. The form element is a container for different types of input elements, such as: text fields, checkboxes, radio buttons, submit buttons, etc.</p>
<h3>Input Element</h3>
<ul><li>The input element is the most used form element.</li><li>An input element can be displayed in many ways, depending on the type attribute.</li>
<h3>Fieldset</h3>
<ul><li>The fieldset tag is used to group related elements in a form.</li></ul>
<h3>Form</h3>
    <form>
    <fieldset style="background-color: aqua;">
        <legend>Information</legend>
        <label for="fname">First name:</label><br>
        <input type="text" id=""fname" name="fname" placeholder="enter name"><br>
    <label for="lname">Last name:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="lname" name="lname"><br>
<label for="pwd">Password:</label><br>
    <input type="pwd" id="pwd"/><br>
    <label for="number">Aadhar number:</label><br>
    <input type="number" id="number"><br>
    <label for="email">Enter your email:</label><br>
    <input type="email" id="email" name="email" placeholder="email"><br>
    <label for="address">Enter your address:</label><br>
    <textarea></textarea><br>
<label for="gender">Enter your gender:</label><br>
<input type="radio" id="gender" name="gender" value="Male"/>Male<br>
<input type="radio" id="gender" name="gender" value="Female"/>Female<br>
<input type="radio" id="gender" name="gender" value="Other"/>Other<br>
<label for="date">Date Of Birth:</label>
<input type="date" id="date" name="date">
<input type="submit" value="Submit"><br>
<label for="status">Marital Status:</label><br>
<input type="checkbox" id="status" name="status" value="status"/>Single<br>
<input type="checkbox" id="status" name="status" value="status"/>Married<br>
<input type="checkbox" id="status" name="status" value="status"/>Widowed<br>
<input type="checkbox" id="status" name="status" value="status"/>Divorced<br>
<label for="favcolor">Select your favorite color:</label><br>
<input type="color" id="favcolor" name="favcolor"><br>
<input type="button" onclick="alert('Thank you')" value="Click Me!"><br>
<input type="submit" value="Submit">
<input type="reset" value="Reset">
    </fieldset>
    </form>
